[The full article, including figures and references is available at the source URL above.

The study is an excellent example of how molecular analysis helps to dissect the epidemiology of an infectious disease.

The epidemiology of _Leishmania_ is complicated, with different strains, reservoirs, and sandfly species. For L. infantum in particular, domestic and wild canids are the natural reservoir, and the authors point out that L. infantum (also often called L. chagasi in Latin America) was introduced to Brazil by dogs brought by colonizers from Portugal and Spain.

The 1st 2 examples A and B above point to increasing human activity, and especially for A, clearing forest for a construction project. Example C is more intriguing, but the clustering with isolates from Europe and Tunisia or Algeria is difficult to explain except by a new and more recent introduction from the Old World. This could be an infected human travelling or an infected pet dog, and it illustrates that diseases travel with their hosts and may establish in new areas if the right climate, vector, and reservoir conditions exist. - Mod.EP

